    <!-- Eye Wellness -->
    <string name="eye_wellness_title">Eye wellness</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_card_description">Learn how the 20·20·20 rule helps your eyes rest.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_view_info_content_description">View information</string>
    <string name="dialog_understood_button">Got it</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_dialog_subtitle">Eye wellness 20·20·20</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_dialog_intro">Prolonged screen use can increase digital eye strain, dry eyes, discomfort from continuous near focus, and sleep disruption when devices are used at night.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_rule_title">20·20·20 rule</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_rule_description">Every 20 minutes, look at an object about 20 feet away (around 6 meters) for 20 seconds.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_less_digital_strain_title">Less digital eye strain</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_less_digital_strain_description">Guided breaks help your eyes stop focusing continuously at close range. The study on the 20·20·20 rule found reduced symptoms of digital eye strain and dry eye.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_blinking_title">More blinking and lubrication</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_blinking_description">When we use screens, we tend to blink less or blink incompletely. Breaks help restore a more natural rhythm of blinking and eye rest.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_prolonged_use_risk_title">Risk from prolonged use</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_prolonged_use_risk_description">Looking at screens for long periods can cause eye fatigue, temporary blurred vision, burning sensations, dry eyes, headaches, and difficulty maintaining focus.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_blue_light_sleep_title">Blue light and nighttime rest</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_blue_light_sleep_description">Blue light from screens, especially at night, can interfere with circadian rhythm and melatonin production, affecting sleep quality.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_attention_title">Attention and mental performance</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_attention_description">Blue light can increase alertness and reaction time during the day, but at night it can be counterproductive by activating the body when it should be preparing to rest.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_duration_matters_title">Duration matters too</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_duration_matters_description">The impact of light does not depend only on color: intensity, exposure time, and timing also matter. That is why taking breaks and reducing intense exposure before sleep is important.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_healthy_tips_title">Healthy tips</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_healthy_tips_body">• Turn on reminders every 20 minutes.\n• Look far away for 20 seconds.\n• Blink consciously during the break.\n• Lower brightness if the room is dark.\n• Avoid intense screens before bed.\n• See a specialist if discomfort persists.</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_references_title">Academic references</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_references_body">Talens-Estarelles, C., Cerviño, A., García-Lázaro, S., Fogelton, A., Sheppard, A., &amp; Wolffsohn, J. S. (2023). The effects of breaks on digital eye strain, dry eye and binocular vision: Testing the 20-20-20 rule. Contact Lens &amp; Anterior Eye, 46(2), 101744. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.clae.2022.101744\n\nHaghani, M., Abbasi, S., Abdoli, L., Shams, S. F., Baha’addini Baigy Zarandi, B. F., Shokrpour, N., Jahromizadeh, A., Mortazavi, S. A., &amp; Mortazavi, S. M. J. (2024). Blue Light and Digital Screens Revisited: A New Look at Blue Light from the Vision Quality, Circadian Rhythm and Cognitive Functions Perspective. Journal of Biomedical Physics and Engineering, 14(3), 213–228. https://doi.org/10.31661/jbpe.v0i0.2106-1355</string>
    <string name="eye_wellness_medical_disclaimer">This information is educational and does not replace a medical evaluation. If you have pain, persistent blurred vision, severe dryness, or frequent discomfort, consult an eye care professional.</string>

